Here above are the explained variance and explained variance ratio we get by using PCA. Notice that the ratio is very high. That can also be seen visually by looking at the plot from part a. Apart from a few outliers, PCA successfully seperates a and b classes. Instances of class "a" have smaller absolute values than that of class "b", reflecting the inner circle - outer circle difference that can be seen from the original 2d plot.

file_names = ["uWaveGestureLibrary_X_TRAIN",
              "uWaveGestureLibrary_Y_TRAIN",
              "uWaveGestureLibrary_Z_TRAIN"]

data = [[], [], []]

for i in range(3):
    for line in open(file_names[i]):
        data[i].append(line.split())
    data[i] = np.array(data[i])
    
data_acc = np.ndarray(shape = (896, 316, 3), dtype = "float")

for i in range(3):
    data_acc[:,:, i] = data[i]

data_v = np.zeros(shape = (896, 316, 3))

data_v[:,0,:] = data_acc[:,0,:]

for instance in range(896):
    for time in range(2, 316):                   
        data_v[instance, time, :] = data_v[instance, time - 1,:] + data_acc[instance, time - 1,:]
        
data_dist = np.zeros(shape = (896, 316, 3))
data_dist[:,0,:] = data_acc[:,0,:]

for instance in range(896):
    for time in range(2, 316):                   
        data_dist[instance, time, :] = data_dist[instance, time - 1,:] + data_v[instance, time - 1,:] + data_acc[instance, time - 1,:]/2

instances = []

for c in range(1,9):
    for instance in range(896):
        if data_v[instance,0,0] == c:
            instances.append(instance)
            break
fig = plt.figure(figsize= (15,8))

labels =["1-Turn Arrow", "Square", "Left arrow", "Right Arrow", 
        "Up Arrow", "Down Arrow ", "Counter-clockwise Turn", "Clockwise Turn"]
for i in range(2):
    for j in range(4):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 4, i*4 + j + 1, projection='3d')
        ax.plot(data_dist[instances[i*4 + j], 1:, 0],
                       data_dist[instances[i*4 + j], 1:, 1],
                       data_dist[instances[i*4 + j], 1:, 2],
                       'gray')
        ax.set_title(labels[i*4 + j], size =15)
        ax.set_xlabel('x')
        ax.set_ylabel('y')
        ax.set_zlabel('z')
        
fig.suptitle("Visualization of One Path from each Class",size = 20)
     
plt.show();

The class labels for each instance is in accordance with the numbers given in the homework. I decided on what class each instance belongs to by basically visualizing the path each instance follows and try to find the moves it makes. To construct the paths, I used basic physics knowledge to find the path from the acceleration data, i.e. $V_{t} = V_{t-1} + a_{t-1}\Delta t$ and $X_{t} = X_{t-1} + V_{t-1}\Delta t + \frac{1}{2}a_{t-1}(\Delta t)^2$. It should be noted that the t-1 velocity and acceleration used to calculate $X_{t}$ since we don't have continuous acceleration data. Furthermore, for easiness, I assumed $\Delta t = 1$. Therefore the equations became:

$V_{t} = V_{t-1} + a_{t-1}$

$X_{t} = X_{t-1} + V_{t-1} + \frac{1}{2}a_{t-1}$

Note that I assumed that $X_{t = 0} = (0, 0, 0)$.Here is some further explanation about why I labeled instances in the way I did:

Class 1: Since the path takes a sharp turn and in none of the other classes there is only one sharp turn

Class 2: Since the path takes three sharp turns.

Class 4: Since the path moves in the -x direction.

Class 3: Since the path moves in the +x direction.

Class 5: Since the path moves in the +z direction.

Class 6: Since the path moves in the -z direction.

Class 8: Since the path takes a counter-clockwise turn.

Class 7: Since the path takes a clockwise turn.

fig = plt.figure(figsize= (15,8))

for i in range(8):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 4, i+1)
    ax.set_title("Eigenvectors for Class "+str(i+1), size =15)
    ax.plot(pca_models[i].components_[0], c = "r")
    ax.plot(pca_models[i].components_[1], c = "b")
    ax.legend(["1st","2nd"])

fig.suptitle("Visualization of First Two Eigenvectors from each Class",size = 20)

plt.show();

These eigenvectors represent the directions to which the represented variance is at the 2-highest values. Representing them as time series, we see the general movement in 3-axes(x,y,z) one after another. An interesting point is that 2 eigenvectors tend to take different signed values, i.e. one is negative when the other is positive and vice versa. Same can be said to the values of them as well. Other than that, for the linear arrows(class 3,4,5,6), direction can be stated by looking at the location of the highest peak of the 1st eigenvector. Instead of this representation, looking these eigenvectors in 2d or 3d space by using x,y,z parts may show more concrete results.
